arget a player who has been eliminated, as it would not change the current game state but could be used to mislead the villagers. However, since we cannot vote for a dead player, I need to consider voting for a player who is currently in a weak position or has low trust. In this case, I do not see a clear target, and voting for a player might raise suspicion on me.\",\n  \"perception_analysis\": \"Voting for a player who has been eliminated would not raise suspicion on me, but it would not provide any strategic advantage. Voting for a living player could make me seem more involved in the game and potentially raise suspicion. Abstaining would show that I am cautious and not jumping to conclusions, which could make me seem more trustworthy. However, it might also make me seem less committed to the game, which could be risky.\",\n  \"final_thought\": \"After careful consideration, I believe that abstaining is the best option. It allows me to avoid raising suspicion on myself and does not provide any strategic advantage to the villagers. I will continue to work on deflecting attention from us and maintaining the trust of the villagers. I will also focus on protecting the Seer and coordinating with my fellow werewolves to avoid premature accusations.\",\n  \"action\": {\n    \"action_vote\": \"abstain\"\n  }\n}}",
